author: Seattle Times staff
title: Hannah Huesers continues her hot streak with a hat trick for Seattle Pacific in 3-1 victory
text:
Hannah Huesers continues her hot streak with a hat trick for Seattle Pacific in 3-1 victory   8:06 pm Junior forward has now scored six goals in past three matches By Seattle Times staff The Seattle Times 
MONMOUTH, Ore. — Hannah Huesers posted her first hat trick and accounted for all the scoring as the Seattle Pacific women’s soccer team score a 3-1 victory on the road over Western Oregon. 
The junior forward scored in the 34th, 63rd and 86th minutes to increase her league-leading total to 10 goals. Huesers, out of Lake Stevens High, topped all GNAC scorers last season with 15 goals. She now has seven multi-goal performances during a 45-game career. 
Seattle Pacific (8-2-1, 4-2-1 Great Northwest) won its third consecutive match. The Wolves (5-5-1) fell to 1-4-1 in GNAC play. 
The hat trick extended a recent hot streak for Huesers. She has six goals during the past three games, all of them 3-1 victories for the Falcons. Most Read Stories Unlimited Digital Access. $1 for 4 weeks. 
Huesers continued her climb up the school’s scoring chart. She has 31 career goals and is tied in fourth-place among SPU scorers with Jocelyn Charette (2007-09). 
Seattle Pacific applied offensive pressure from the opening whistle and tried the game’s first four shots, including an attempt from Huesers just 28 seconds in that was saved. 
Huesers secured the victory with an unassisted strike at 85:55. She stripped the ball from a defender and delivered a shot to the bottom left of the goal. 
Goalkeeper Molly Stinson stopped one shot for SPU. OTHER WOMEN’S SOCCER 
• Second-half goals by Elise Aylward and Emily Webster pushed host Western Washington (11-0, 6-0 Great Northwest) to a 2-0 victory over Montana State Billings (5-4-2, 3-3-1) . 
• Southern Oregon’s Allyson Ward scored on a header in the second overtime as the Raiders (6-7-2, 5-3 Cascade) were 2-1 winners over Northwest (4-7-1, 3-2) in Kirkland. MEN’S SOCCER 
• Branson Corwin scored two goals as Northwest (7-5, 5-2 CCC) recorded a 3-0 shutout of visiting Southern Oregon (10-5, 5-5). Kyle Zimmerman scored the other goal for the Eagles and Daniel Christenson earned the shutout. ROWING 
• Gonzaga’s men’s varsity eight crew turned in the fastest time of the day at 16:25 for 5,000 meters to beat Washington State in the Head of the Spokane on the Spokane River. In women’s varsity four, WSU won in 18:45 with the Zags second. CROSS COUNTRY 
• Sarah Inglis of Trinity Western won her third consecutive title in the women’s race at the Western Washington Invitational and led her teammates to the team title as well. Inglis shaved five seconds off her course-record time of a year ago, finishing the 6,000-meter race in 20:47, some 32 seconds ahead of her nearest competitor. On the men’s side, Henry Cheseto won the individual crown and helped Alaska Anchorage to the team title. Host WWU finished fourth among 13 women’s teams and sixth among the 14 men’s teams. VOLLEYBALL 
• Savannah Blinn hit a blistering .615, posting 18 kills and two attack errors on 26 attempts in leading Gonzaga past visiting Pepperdine 25-17, 25-16, 25-20). 
• Host Utah Valley (8-9, 4-1 Western Athletic) jumped out to a big lead in the first set and continued to a 25-17, 25-16, 26-24 victory over Seattle University (11-7, 3-2). Martina Samadan led the Redhawks with eight kills. 
• On the road in Klamath Falls, Northwest (13-6, 9-5) rallied from a three-point deficit in the final set to post an 18-25, 25-19, 25-15, 20-25, 15-9 victory over Oregon Tech (11-7, 6-6). Mattie Jo Johnson led the Northwest attack with 12 kills followed by Amanda Waterman with 11 in the victory. SWIMMING 
• Washington State won two more events, but still dropped a dual meet to visiting California, losing 299.5-131.5. Presley Wetterstrom picked up her second victory of the two-day meet in the 200-yard breaststroke for the Cougars with a time of 2:16.53. Linnea Lindberg won the 50 breaststroke in 30.19 for WSU. From sports-information reports.
